b'' b'' b' try this after xcreatewindow:' b' b' b'' b' xsizehints-flags usposition ussize;\t/* or pposition psize b' b' xsetwmnormalhints (display, window, xsizehints);' b' b'' b' these hints tell the window manager that the position and size of the window' b' are specified by the users and that the window manager should accept these' b' values. if you use xsizehints-flags pposition psize, this tells the window' b' manager that the values are prefered values of the program, not the user.' b" i don't know a window manager that doesn't place the window like you prefer" b' if you specify the position and size like above.' b'' b"sorry, but olwm and tvtwm don't do it. they place the title at that position" b'and the window at a position below it.' b'' b'this becomes a problem when you want a program to be able to save its current' b'configuration and restore is later.' b'' b'currently, my solution is:' b'' b'xcreatewindow(...);' b'xsetwmproperties(..);' b'xmapwindow(...);' b'xflush(...);' b'xmovewindow(...);' b'' b'' b'it works with olwm, but is less than elegant. all this leaves me wondering' b"if i'm overlooking something obvious." b'' b'richard.' b'' 